title: For Sale:  Rare 5mm (Pinfire) Dolne-Bar Patent 'Apache' Knuckle-Duster
postcontent: $9,975.00 obo - A RARE BELGIAN 5mm (PINFIRE) DOLNE-BAR PATENT 'APACHE' SIX-SHOT SELF-COCKING KNUCKLE-DUSTER REVOLVER BY L. DOLNE, SERIAL NO. 5222, CIRCA 1875 With fluted barrel-block, metal frame marked 'L. DOLNE INV. UR' on one side, folding trigger, folding knuckle-duster grip, and short locking bayonet with waved blade fitted to the left side of the frame.  1 9/26 in (4 cm) barrel-block.Serial #5222, 5 mm Pinfire, 1.5" fluted barrel cluster.  This sinister looking Dolne marked pepperbox was the brainchild of Mr. Louis Dolne of Liege and combines a folding set of brass knuckles with both a six-shot pinfire revolver and a swing-out 2 7/8" double-edged, flambard (flame shaped) blade.The spring latches for the knife blad and the grip are original and still lock firmly in place.  The revolver mechanism is fully functional although I have never fired it.These curious firearms were quite popular with the thugs and toughs of the late 19th century Parisian underworld, known as "les Apaches" for their brutal nature, and it was from them that these little revolvers received their familiar nickname.  This example is in good condition but looks fantastic and would make a great additino to any collection of firearms curiousities or gambling paraphernalia.The design dates from the 1860's, and is attributed to Louis Dolne.  The gun was manufactured through the end of the 1800's.  The gun operates on the principle of a pepperbox revolver using a pinfire action and incorporates a fold-over knuckle duster forming the grip and also a rudimentary foldout, dual-edged knife.Due to the lack of a barrel, the revolver's effective range is very limited, but since all of its component parts can be folded inward towards the cylinder, it was easily concealable inside a pocket.  It was common to leave an empty chamber with no cartridge under the firing pin to prevent shooting oneself while having it concealed in a pocket or bag, as the weapon has no trigger guard or safety.  This weapon is not able to be aimed precisely because of its lack of front and rear sights.  Despite its limited potential, the revolver proved deadly at extremely close range.Les Apaches (French) were members of a Parisian Belle Epoque underworld subculture.  Apaches were so called because of their alleged savagery was compared with that attributed by Europeans to the Native American tribes of Apaches.  The Apaches were especially associated with some districts of Paris: Belleville, La Bastille, La Villette and Montmartre which was also home to the famous Moulin Rouge dance hall and nightclub.During their heyday, the prospect of being mugged or otherwise assaulted by Apache gangsters was especially feared by members of the emergent bourgeois middle class.  Some of the gangs used a unique type of pistol which was named the "Apache revolver" or "Apache pistol":  a pinfire cartridge revolver with no barrel, a set of foldover brass knuckles for a handgrip, and a folding knife mounted right underneath the revolver drum for use as a stabbing weapon.

title: For Sale:  12 Guage/.410 Pump Gun Pair!!
postcontent: Remember the days when your local hardware store sold their own branded firearms?  When you could order from Sears, Montgomery Wards and others?  My parents had a "mom and pop" operated Western Auto Store since before I could remember and thus I knd of "grew up" in the business.  As a result, I've always had an affinity to these Western Auto "store branded" firearms but I have to start thinning out some of the duplicates!  Here we have a pair that represent some of the best.The 12 guage is a Revelation R310ABR that translates into a Mossberg 500 that shoots both 2 3/4" and 3" and started out as a "Slugster".  So, it has the 24" smooth bore barrel with rifle sights.  A couple of years ago I bought a hard-to-find 30" full-choke, vent rib barrel.  As is typical with these venerable Mossbergs, it's an accurate gun with both the slug barrel (considering a smooth bore and open sights) and throws a very good pattern with the 30".  I've shot some trap with the long barrel and it's always fun to rotate through the five stations with your Western Auto shotgun and break 22 next to the guy who also broke 22 but is shooting a Perazzi.  The "Slugster Barrel" has 90%+ blue but the guy I bought the 30" barrel from was going to refinish the barrel and it looks like he had gently wire brushed it.  I didn't care care because I was more interested in shooting it and, as mentioned, the 30" barrels are harder to find.  The bores on both are perfect.  The action is mechanically perfect but, as you know, the 500's have an alloy receiver so it has the usual wear marks where the slide touches it, etc.  There is also a small hole drilled into the bottom of the forearm.  I'm guessing that someone probably had a nylon or leather strap attached there at some time, as was commonly done 30 or 40 years ago.The .410 is a Revelation 300F which means it's actually a Stevens 77.  This one is a NSN (No Serial Number) gun, which means it pre-dates the Gun Control Act of 1968.  LOTS of, if not most, inexpensive .410's get cut down into "youth" models over the years but this one is truly a "survivor" is that it still unaltered (i.e., stock dimensions are adult-sized) and has a very rare vent rib barrel.  This shotgun still has 85%+ of the original bluing, a perfect bore and, although I have not shot it, it functions perfectly.  This is a combo deal, both guns for one money.
